  "text": "where µ is a constant of order unity and r A is the Alfvén radius, defined as the point where the stellar wind radial velocity reaches the Alfvén velocity. The magnitude of µ varies depending upon the assumed magnetic topology [CITATION_1] but its value will not be important to our calculations below. In most previous treatments, the torqueL is assumed to act perfectly anti-parallel to the stellar spin axis, leading to a deceleration of Ω , but no change in the stellar orientation. However, the stellar wind launching mechanisms are highly turbulent [CITATION_2] , and the magnetosphere of the Sun itself is time-variable and nonazimuthally symmetric [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Therefore, it is unlikely that the angular momentum lost is directed identically along the rotation axis.",
